            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <h2>Platform Updates This Week</h2>
<p>Three signals deserve attention:</p>
<p><strong>Meta</strong> further tightened ad serving restrictions for Pages with scores below 3, with some e-commerce clients reporting a 30%+ drop in delivery; <strong>Google</strong> launched a new policy violation appeal process, extending response times from 48 hours to 5-7 business days; <strong>TikTok</strong> began batch-limiting accounts with high creative repetition rates.</p>
<p>These three updates point to the same trend—platforms are using more refined rules to force advertisers toward self-regulation. The window for multi-account operations is narrowing, and the rough approach of relying on volume to beat probability is becoming significantly riskier.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Logic 1: Tier by Risk Level, Not by Business Line</h2>
<p>Many teams segment accounts by product line—Account A for Product A, Account B for Product B. While reasonable in early stages, this approach creates massive management redundancy once account numbers exceed 10.</p>
<p>A more practical tiering logic is <strong>segmenting by risk tolerance</strong>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Core Accounts (Tier 1)</strong>: Daily budget $500+, stable delivery, contributing 60%+ of team GMV.<br />
<strong>Test Accounts (Tier 2)</strong>: Daily budget $100-$500, handling new creative, targeting tests.<br />
<strong>Buffer Accounts (Tier 3)</strong>: Daily budget under $100, or newly opened accounts not yet scaled, for high-risk creative and extreme targeting tests.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Practical recommendations this week</strong>:<br />
- List Tier 1 Page scores as mandatory daily morning meeting checks; activate creative replacement plans immediately when scores fall below 3.5<br />
- Tier 3 accounts should use independent IP and device environments, avoiding shared login environments with Tier 1</p>
<hr />
<h2>Logic 2: Budget Allocation from "Equal Distribution" to "Dynamic Adjustment"</h2>
<p>A common pitfall for multi-account teams is budget equalization—$200 per account, which appears fair but is actually an efficiency killer. High-performing accounts don't get enough ammunition, while test accounts fail to gather valid data due to insufficient budgets.</p>
<p><strong>This week's recommendation: adopt the "532 Budget Model"</strong>:</p>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Tier</th>
<th>Account Count Share</th>
<th>Budget Share</th>
<th>Adjustment Frequency</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Tier 1</td>
<td>20%</td>
<td>50%</td>
<td>Weekly evaluation</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Tier 2</td>
<td>30%</td>
<td>30%</td>
<td>Every 3 days</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Tier 3</td>
<td>50%</td>
<td>20%</td>
<td>Can be paused anytime</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<p><strong>A specific scenario</strong>: A cross-border e-commerce team consolidated budgets from 3 Tier 2 test accounts before Black Friday, concentrating resources into the top-performing account, raising its daily budget from $150 to $600. Conversion costs dropped 18% on the big sale day.</p>
<hr />
<h2>Logic 3: Recharge and Balance Management is a Hidden Cost of Tiering</h2>
<p>Many teams do well on account tiering but have chaotic recharge management—either insufficient balances causing delivery interruptions, or idle balances across many accounts tying up cash flow.</p>
<p><strong>This week's reminders</strong>:<br />
- Set Tier 1 balance alerts to trigger when balance falls below 3 days' spend; Tier 3 can be set at less than 1 day's spend<br />
- Monthly recharges should be concentrated at the beginning of the month, avoiding mid-month frequent operations that could trigger account anomaly flags<br />
- Multi-account teams should use unified recharge dashboards for centralized management, avoiding individual account logins that cause IP fluctuations</p>
<hr />
<h2>This Week's Recommendations</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Complete an account tiering audit this week</strong>: Reorganize existing account counts and budget distribution according to the three-tier model above; the goal is for Tier 3 accounts to not exceed 40% of total</li>
<li><strong>Set Page scores as a shared team dashboard metric</strong>: No longer letting a single optimizer monitor alone, reducing risk exposure from personnel changes</li>
<li><strong>Tighten Tier 3 access before Black Friday/Cyber Monday</strong>: Pause new account openings, concentrate resources to stabilize Tier 1 and Tier 2 delivery states</li>
</ol>
<p>The essence of multi-account management is not "managing accounts" but <strong>managing risk and efficiency</strong>. Once tiering is clear, you'll find that many operational problems (creative collisions, policy violations by association, budget waste) are actually secondary issues caused by unclear tiering.</p>
